1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:01,200
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,200 --> 00:00:02,520
THE BOY WHO LIVED

3
00:00:02,520 --> 00:00:04,200
Mr. and Mrs. Dursley,

4
00:00:04,200 --> 00:00:05,240
of number four,

5
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:06,200
Privet Drive,

6
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:08,880
were proud to say that they were perfectly normal,

7
00:00:08,880 --> 00:00:10,280
thank you very much.

8
00:00:10,280 --> 00:00:14,960
They were the last people you'd expect to be 
involved in anything strange or mysterious,

9
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,720
because they just didn't hold with such nonsense.

10
00:00:17,720 --> 00:00:20,800
Mr. Dursley was the director 
of a firm called Grunnings,

11
00:00:20,800 --> 00:00:22,080
which made drills.

12
00:00:22,080 --> 00:00:23,120
He was a big,

13
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:25,280
beefy man with hardly any neck,

14
00:00:25,280 --> 00:00:27,840
although he did have a very large mustache.

15
00:00:27,840 --> 00:00:32,320
Mrs. Dursley was thin and blonde and had 
nearly twice the usual amount of neck,

16
00:00:32,320 --> 00:00:37,000
which came in very useful as she spent so 
much of her time craning over garden fences,

17
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:38,480
spying on the neighbors.

18
00:00:38,480 --> 00:00:40,600
The Dursleys had a small son called Dudley

19
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:43,600
and in their opinion there 
was no finer boy anywhere.

20
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:45,680
The Dursleys had everything they wanted,

21
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:47,440
but they also had a secret,

22
00:00:47,440 --> 00:00:50,480
and their greatest fear was 
that somebody would discover it.

23
00:00:50,480 --> 00:00:54,120
They didn't think they could bear it 
if anyone found out about the Potters.

24
00:00:54,120 --> 00:00:56,640
Mrs. Potter was Mrs. Dursley's sister,

25
00:00:56,640 --> 00:00:58,680
but they hadn't met for several years;

26
00:00:58,680 --> 00:01:02,360
in fact, Mrs. Dursley pretended 
she didn't have a sister,

27
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:04,800
because her sister and her 
good-for-nothing husband  

28
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:07,560
were as unDursleyish as it was possible to be.

29
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:08,800
The Dursleys shuddered to think

30
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:12,080
what the neighbors would say if 
the Potters arrived in the street.

31
00:01:12,080 --> 00:01:14,680
The Dursleys knew that the 
Potters had a small son,

32
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:17,280
too, but they had never even seen him.

33
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:20,440
This boy was another good reason 
for keeping the Potters away;

34
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:23,160
they didn't want Dudley 
mixing with a child like that.

35
00:01:23,160 --> 00:01:25,760
When Mr. and Mrs. Dursley woke up on the dull,

36
00:01:25,760 --> 00:01:27,800
gray Tuesday our story starts,

37
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:31,280
there was nothing about the cloudy 
sky outside to suggest that strange

38
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:34,960
and mysterious things would soon 
be happening all over the country.

39
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:38,400
Mr. Dursley hummed as he picked 
out his most boring tie for work,

40
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:43,520
and Mrs. Dursley gossiped away happily as she 
wrestled a screaming Dudley into his high chair.

41
00:01:43,520 --> 00:01:47,200
None of them noticed a large, 
tawny owl flutter past the window.

42
00:01:47,200 --> 00:01:48,400
At half past eight,

43
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:50,440
Mr. Dursley picked up his briefcase,

44
00:01:50,440 --> 00:01:52,280
pecked Mrs. Dursley on the cheek,

45
00:01:52,280 --> 00:01:54,720
and tried to kiss Dudley good-bye but missed,

46
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:59,400
because Dudley was now having a tantrum 
and throwing his cereal at the walls.

47
00:01:59,400 --> 00:02:00,200
"Little tyke,"

48
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:02,760
chortled Mr. Dursley as he left the house.

49
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:06,320
He got into his car and backed 
out of number four's drive.

50
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:10,680
It was on the corner of the street that he 
noticed the first sign of something peculiar ,

51
00:02:10,680 --> 00:02:12,240
a cat reading a map.

52
00:02:12,240 --> 00:02:13,160
For a second,

53
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:15,600
Mr. Dursley didn't realize what he had seen ,

54
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:17,800
then he jerked his head around to look again.

55
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:20,960
There was a tabby cat standing 
on the corner of Privet Drive,

56
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:22,840
but there wasn't a map in sight.

57
00:02:22,840 --> 00:02:24,440
What could he have been thinking of?

58
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:26,200
It must have been a trick of the light.

59
00:02:26,200 --> 00:02:28,720
Mr. Dursley blinked and stared at the cat.

60
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:30,080
It stared back.

61
00:02:30,080 --> 00:02:33,080
As Mr. Dursley drove around 
the corner and up the road,

62
00:02:33,080 --> 00:02:34,960
he watched the cat in his mirror.

63
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:37,680
It was now reading the sign 
that said Privet Drive ,

64
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:39,200
no, looking at the sign;

65
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:41,440
cats couldn't read maps or signs.

66
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:45,360
Mr. Dursley gave himself a little 
shake and put the cat out of his mind.

67
00:02:45,360 --> 00:02:49,920
As he drove toward town he thought of nothing 
except a large order of drills he was hoping

68
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:51,040
to get that day.

69
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:52,200
But on the edge of town,

70
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:55,040
drills were driven out of 
his mind by something else.

71
00:02:55,040 --> 00:02:57,440
As he sat in the usual morning traffic jam,

72
00:02:57,440 --> 00:03:01,880
he couldn't help noticing that there seemed 
to be a lot of strangely dressed people about.

73
00:03:01,880 --> 00:03:03,280
People in cloaks.

74
00:03:03,280 --> 00:03:06,320
Mr. Dursley couldn't bear people 
who dressed in funny clothes ,

75
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:08,440
the getups you saw on young people!

76
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:10,960
He supposed this was some stupid new fashion.

77
00:03:10,960 --> 00:03:12,880
He drummed his fingers on the steering wheel

78
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:16,840
and his eyes fell on a huddle of 
these weirdos standing quite close by.

79
00:03:16,840 --> 00:03:19,160
They were whispering excitedly together.

80
00:03:19,160 --> 00:03:23,120
Mr. Dursley was enraged to see that a 
couple of them weren't young at all;

81
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:25,520
why, that man had to be older than he was,

82
00:03:25,520 --> 00:03:27,560
and wearing an emerald-green cloak!

83
00:03:27,560 --> 00:03:28,640
The nerve of him!

84
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:32,240
But then it struck Mr. Dursley that 
this was probably some silly stunt ,

85
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:35,120
these people were obviously 
collecting for something...

86
00:03:35,120 --> 00:03:36,640
yes, that would be it.

87
00:03:36,640 --> 00:03:39,280
The traffic moved on and a few minutes later,

88
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:42,000
Mr. Dursley arrived in the Grunnings parking lot,

89
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,800
his mind back on drills.

90
00:03:43,800 --> 00:03:48,320
Mr. Dursley always sat with his back to the 
window in his office on the ninth floor.

91
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:49,080
If he hadn't,

92
00:03:49,080 --> 00:03:52,520
he might have found it harder to 
concentrate on drills that morning.

93
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:55,520
He didn't see the owls swoop 
ing past in broad daylight,

94
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:57,440
though people down in the street did;

95
00:03:57,440 --> 00:04:01,280
they pointed and gazed open- mouthed 
as owl after owl sped overhead.

96
00:04:01,280 --> 00:04:04,120
Most of them had never seen 
an owl even at nighttime.

97
00:04:04,120 --> 00:04:05,120
Mr. Dursley,

98
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:07,000
however, had a perfectly normal,

99
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,200
owl-free morning.

100
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:10,240
He yelled at five different people.

101
00:04:10,240 --> 00:04:13,760
He made several important telephone 
calls and shouted a bit more.

102
00:04:13,760 --> 00:04:16,280
He was in a very good mood until lunchtime,

103
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:17,760
when he thought he'd stretch his legs

104
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:21,080
and walk across the road to buy 
himself a bun from the bakery.

105
00:04:21,080 --> 00:04:22,520
He'd forgotten all about the people

106
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:25,880
in cloaks until he passed a group 
of them next to the baker's.

107
00:04:25,880 --> 00:04:27,840
He eyed them angrily as he passed.

108
00:04:27,840 --> 00:04:28,880
He didn't know why,

109
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:30,520
but they made him uneasy.

110
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:32,320
This bunch were whispering excitedly,

111
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:35,400
too, and he couldn't see a single collecting tin.

112
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:37,160
It was on his way back past them,

113
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:39,240
clutching a large doughnut in a bag,

114
00:04:39,240 --> 00:04:41,720
that he caught a few words 
of what they were saying.

115
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:42,600
"The Potters,

116
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:43,360
that's right,

117
00:04:43,360 --> 00:04:45,240
that's what I heard yes,

118
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:46,800
their son, Harry"

119
00:04:46,800 --> 00:04:48,480
Mr. Dursley stopped dead.

120
00:04:48,480 --> 00:04:49,640
Fear flooded him.

121
00:04:49,640 --> 00:04:53,360
He looked back at the whisperers as 
if he wanted to say something to them,

122
00:04:53,360 --> 00:04:54,720
but thought better of it.

123
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:56,640
He dashed back across the road,

124
00:04:56,640 --> 00:04:58,040
hurried up to his office,

125
00:04:58,040 --> 00:05:00,520
snapped at his secretary not to disturb him,

126
00:05:00,520 --> 00:05:01,960
seized his telephone,

127
00:05:01,960 --> 00:05:05,760
and had almost finished dialing his 
home number when he changed his mind.

128
00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:08,720
He put the receiver back down 
and stroked his mustache,

129
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:09,360
thinking...

130
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:11,280
no, he was being stupid.

131
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:13,480
Potter wasn't such an unusual name.

132
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:17,480
He was sure there were lots of people 
called Potter who had a son called Harry.

133
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:18,520
Come to think of it,

134
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:21,200
he wasn't even sure his nephew was called Harry.

135
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:22,920
He'd never even seen the boy.

136
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:25,400
It might have been Harvey. Or Harold.

137
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:27,680
There was no point in worrying Mrs. Dursley;

138
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:31,000
she always got so upset at 
any mention of her sister.

139
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:32,160
He didn't blame her ,

140
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:34,440
if he'd had a sister like that...

141
00:05:34,440 --> 00:05:35,480
but all the same,

142
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:37,480
those people in cloaks...

143
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:40,880
He found it a lot harder to concentrate 
on drills that afternoon and

144
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:43,520
when he left the building at five o'clock,

145
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:47,720
he was still so worried that he walked 
straight into someone just outside the door.

146
00:05:47,720 --> 00:05:48,240
"Sorry,"

147
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:48,960
he grunted,

148
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:51,760
as the tiny old man stumbled and almost fell.

149
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:56,880
It was a few seconds before Mr. Dursley realized 
that the man was wearing a violet cloak.

150
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:59,640
He didn't seem at all upset at 
being almost knocked to the ground.

151
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:01,440
On the contrary,

152
00:06:01,440 --> 00:06:06,720
his face split into a wide smile and he said 
in a squeaky voice that made passersby stare,

153
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:07,840
"Don't be sorry,

154
00:06:07,840 --> 00:06:08,840
my dear sir,

155
00:06:08,840 --> 00:06:10,800
for nothing could upset me today!

156
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:13,400
Rejoice, for You-Know-Who has gone at last!

157
00:06:13,400 --> 00:06:15,800
Even Muggles like yourself should be celebrating,

158
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:16,560
this happy,

159
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:17,440
happy day!"

160
00:06:17,440 --> 00:06:21,200
And the old man hugged Mr. Dursley 
around the middle and walked off.

161
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:23,480
Mr. Dursley stood rooted to the spot.

162
00:06:23,480 --> 00:06:25,920
He had been hugged by a complete stranger.

163
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:27,960
He also thought he had been called a Muggle,

164
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:29,080
whatever that was.

165
00:06:29,080 --> 00:06:30,200
He was rattled.

166
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:32,800
He hurried to his car and set off for home,

167
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:34,640
hoping he was imagining things,

168
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:36,440
which he had never hoped before,

169
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:39,320
because he didn't approve of imagination.

170
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:41,680
As he pulled into the driveway of number four,

171
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:43,400
the first thing he saw ,

172
00:06:43,400 --> 00:06:45,120
and it didn't improve his mood ,

173
00:06:45,120 --> 00:06:47,480
was the tabby cat he'd spotted that morning.

174
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:49,640
It was now sitting on his garden wall.

175
00:06:49,640 --> 00:06:51,240
He was sure it was the same one;

176
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:53,680
it had the same markings around its eyes.

177
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:54,320
"Shoo!"

178
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:56,080
said Mr. Dursley loudly.

179
00:06:56,080 --> 00:06:57,440
The cat didn't move.

180
00:06:57,440 --> 00:06:59,200
It just gave him a stern look.

181
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:01,680
Was this normal cat behavior?

182
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:03,080
Mr. Dursley wondered.

183
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:04,720
Trying to pull himself together,

184
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:06,640
he let himself into the house.

185
00:07:06,640 --> 00:07:09,960
He was still determined not to 
mention anything to his wife.

186
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:11,600
Mrs. Dursley had had a nice,

187
00:07:11,600 --> 00:07:12,600
normal day.

188
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:16,600
She told him over dinner all about Mrs. 
Next Door's problems with her daughter and

189
00:07:16,600 --> 00:07:19,380
how Dudley had learned a new word (

190
00:07:19,380 --> 00:07:19,760
"Won't!" ).

191
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:21,880
Mr. Dursley tried to act normally.

192
00:07:21,880 --> 00:07:23,560
When Dudley had been put to bed,

193
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:28,000
he went into the living room in time to 
catch the last report on the evening news:

194
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:28,720
"And finally,

195
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:30,600
bird-watchers everywhere have reported

196
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:34,160
that the nation's owls have been 
behaving very unusually today.

197
00:07:34,160 --> 00:07:38,120
Although owls normally hunt at night 
and are hardly ever seen in daylight,

198
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:40,640
there have been hundreds of 
sightings of these birds flying

199
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:43,000
in every direction since sunrise.

200
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,560
Experts are unable to explain why the owls 
have suddenly changed their sleeping pattern."

201
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:49,960
The newscaster allowed himself a grin.

202
00:07:49,960 --> 00:07:51,440
"Most mysterious.

203
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:54,000
And now, over to Jim McGuffin with the weather.

204
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,960
Going to be any more showers of owls tonight,

205
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:56,720
Jim?"

206
00:07:56,720 --> 00:07:57,640
"Well, Ted,"

207
00:07:57,640 --> 00:07:58,800
said the weatherman,

208
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:00,240
"I don't know about that,

209
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:03,200
but it's not only the owls that 
have been acting oddly today.

210
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:05,160
Viewers as far apart as Kent,

211
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:10,080
Yorkshire, and Dundee have been phoning in to tell 
me that instead of the rain I promised yesterday,

212
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:12,440
they've had a downpour of shooting stars!

213
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:15,360
Perhaps people have been 
celebrating Bonfire Night early ,

214
00:08:15,360 --> 00:08:17,760
it's not until next week, folks!

215
00:08:17,760 --> 00:08:20,080
But I can promise a wet night tonight."

216
00:08:20,080 --> 00:08:22,600
Mr. Dursley sat frozen in his armchair.

217
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:24,440
Shooting stars all over Britain?

218
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:26,240
Owls flying by daylight?

219
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:28,880
Mysterious people in cloaks all over the place?

220
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:29,880
And a whisper,

221
00:08:29,880 --> 00:08:32,040
a whisper about the Potters...

222
00:08:32,040 --> 00:08:35,640
Mrs. Dursley came into the living 
room carrying two cups of tea.

223
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:36,760
It was no good.

224
00:08:36,760 --> 00:08:38,560
He'd have to say something to her.

225
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:40,480
He cleared his throat nervously.

226
00:08:40,480 --> 00:08:41,800
"Er , Petunia,

227
00:08:41,800 --> 00:08:44,520
dear , you haven't heard from your sister lately,

228
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:45,240
have you?"

229
00:08:45,240 --> 00:08:46,480
As he had expected,

230
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:48,920
Mrs. Dursley looked shocked and angry.

231
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:52,280
After all, they normally pretended 
she didn't have a sister.

232
00:08:52,280 --> 00:08:52,680
"No,"

233
00:08:52,680 --> 00:08:54,080
she said sharply.

234
00:08:54,080 --> 00:08:54,640
"Why?"

235
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:55,880
"Funny stuff on the news,"

236
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:58,080
Mr. Dursley mumbled. "Owls...

237
00:08:58,080 --> 00:08:59,720
shooting stars...

238
00:08:59,720 --> 00:09:03,120
and there were a lot of funny-looking 
people in town today..."

239
00:09:03,120 --> 00:09:03,560
"So?"

240
00:09:03,560 --> 00:09:05,320
snapped Mrs. Dursley.

241
00:09:05,320 --> 00:09:07,600
"Well, I just thought... maybe...

242
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:08,960
it was something to do with...

243
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:09,720
you know...

244
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:10,840
her crowd."

245
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:13,600
Mrs. Dursley sipped her tea through pursed lips.

246
00:09:13,600 --> 00:09:16,680
Mr. Dursley wondered whether he 
dared tell her he'd heard the name

247
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:17,520
"Potter."

248
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:22,000
He decided he didn't dare. Instead 
he said, as casually as he could,

249
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,520
"Their son , he'd be about 
Dudley's age now, wouldn't he?"

250
00:09:25,520 --> 00:09:26,560
"I suppose so,"

251
00:09:26,560 --> 00:09:28,320
said Mrs. Dursley stiffly.

252
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:30,920
"What's his name again? Howard, isn't it?"

253
00:09:30,920 --> 00:09:34,480
"Harry. Nasty, common name, if you ask me."

254
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:35,840
"Oh, yes,"

255
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:38,680
said Mr. Dursley, his heart sinking horribly.

256
00:09:38,680 --> 00:09:40,920
"Yes, I quite agree."

257
00:09:40,920 --> 00:09:44,560
He didn't say another word on the 
subject as they went upstairs to bed.

258
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:46,560
While Mrs. Dursley was in the bathroom,

259
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:50,840
Mr. Dursley crept to the bedroom window 
and peered down into the front garden.

260
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:52,240
The cat was still there.

261
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:55,880
It was staring down Privet Drive as 
though it were waiting for something.

262
00:09:55,880 --> 00:09:57,480
Was he imagining things?

263
00:09:57,480 --> 00:09:59,320
Could all this have anything 
to do with the Potters?

264
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:00,760
If it did...

265
00:10:00,760 --> 00:10:03,320
if it got out that they 
were related to a pair of ,

266
00:10:03,320 --> 00:10:05,400
well, he didn't think he could bear it.

267
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:07,120
The Dursleys got into bed.

268
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:10,600
Mrs. Dursley fell asleep quickly 
but Mr. Dursley lay awake,

269
00:10:10,600 --> 00:10:12,560
turning it all over in his mind.

270
00:10:12,560 --> 00:10:17,320
His last, comforting thought before he fell 
asleep was that even if the Potters were involved,

271
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:20,920
there was no reason for them to 
come near him and Mrs. Dursley.

272
00:10:20,920 --> 00:10:25,280
The Potters knew very well what he and 
Petunia thought about them and their kind....

273
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:29,600
He couldn't see how he and Petunia could get 
mixed up in anything that might be going on ,

274
00:10:29,600 --> 00:10:31,280
he yawned and turned over ,

275
00:10:31,280 --> 00:10:32,880
it couldn't affect them....

276
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:34,520
How very wrong he was.

277
00:10:34,520 --> 00:10:37,640
Mr. Dursley might have been 
drifting into an uneasy sleep,

278
00:10:37,640 --> 00:10:42,040
but the cat on the wall outside 
was showing no sign of sleepiness.

279
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:44,000
It was sitting as still as a statue,

280
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,520
its eyes fixed unblinkingly on 
the far corner of Privet Drive.

281
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:50,960
It didn't so much as quiver when a 
car door slammed on the next street,

282
00:10:50,960 --> 00:10:53,280
nor when two owls swooped overhead.

283
00:10:53,280 --> 00:10:56,680
In fact, it was nearly midnight 
before the cat moved at all.

284
00:10:56,680 --> 00:10:59,400
A man appeared on the corner 
the cat had been watching,

285
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:03,640
appeared so suddenly and silently you'd have 
thought he'd just popped out of the ground.

286
00:11:03,640 --> 00:11:06,200
The cat's tail twitched and its eyes narrowed.

287
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:09,360
Nothing like this man had ever 
been seen on Privet Drive.

288
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:10,360
He was tall,

289
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:12,040
thin, and very old,

290
00:11:12,040 --> 00:11:14,480
judging by the silver of his hair and beard,

291
00:11:14,480 --> 00:11:16,920
which were both long enough to tuck into his belt.

292
00:11:16,920 --> 00:11:18,520
He was wearing long robes,

293
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:20,560
a purple cloak that swept the ground,

294
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:21,560
and high-heeled,

295
00:11:21,560 --> 00:11:22,760
buckled boots.

296
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:24,360
His blue eyes were light,

297
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:29,240
bright, and sparkling behind half-moon spectacles 
and his nose was very long and crooked,

298
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:32,120
as though it had been broken at least twice.

299
00:11:32,120 --> 00:11:34,480
This man's name was Albus Dumbledore.

300
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:38,280
Albus Dumbledore didn't seem to realize 
that he had just arrived in a street

301
00:11:38,280 --> 00:11:41,160
where everything from his name 
to his boots was unwelcome.

302
00:11:41,160 --> 00:11:43,080
He was busy rummaging in his cloak,

303
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:44,320
looking for something.

304
00:11:44,320 --> 00:11:46,880
But he did seem to realize he was being watched,

305
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:49,000
because he looked up suddenly at the cat,

306
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,800
which was still staring at him 
from the other end of the street.

307
00:11:51,800 --> 00:11:52,760
For some reason,

308
00:11:52,760 --> 00:11:54,960
the sight of the cat seemed to amuse him.

309
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,240
He chuckled and muttered,

310
00:11:56,240 --> 00:11:57,480
"I should have known."

311
00:11:57,480 --> 00:12:00,280
He found what he was looking 
for in his inside pocket.

312
00:12:00,280 --> 00:12:02,680
It seemed to be a silver cigarette lighter.

313
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:03,880
He flicked it open,

314
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:05,080
held it up in the air,

315
00:12:05,080 --> 00:12:06,160
and clicked it.

316
00:12:06,160 --> 00:12:09,160
The nearest street lamp 
went out with a little pop.

317
00:12:09,160 --> 00:12:10,280
He clicked it again ,

318
00:12:10,280 --> 00:12:12,520
the next lamp flickered into darkness.

319
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:14,440
Twelve times he clicked the Put-Outer,

320
00:12:14,440 --> 00:12:18,800
until the only lights left on the whole street 
were two tiny pinpricks in the distance,

321
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:20,920
which were the eyes of the cat watching him.

322
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:22,720
If anyone looked out of their window now,

323
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,440
even beady-eyed Mrs. Dursley,

324
00:12:24,440 --> 00:12:27,960
they wouldn't be able to see anything 
that was happening down on the pavement.

325
00:12:27,960 --> 00:12:30,680
Dumbledore slipped the 
Put-Outer back inside his cloak

326
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:33,240
and set off down the street toward number four,

327
00:12:33,240 --> 00:12:35,760
where he sat down on the wall next to the cat.

328
00:12:35,760 --> 00:12:36,880
He didn't look at it,

329
00:12:36,880 --> 00:12:39,000
but after a moment he spoke to it.

330
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,760
"Fancy seeing you here, Professor McGonagall."

331
00:12:41,760 --> 00:12:43,440
He turned to smile at the tabby,

332
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:44,640
but it had gone.

333
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:47,320
Instead he was smiling at a 
rather severe-looking woman

334
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:49,840
who was wearing square glasses exactly the shape

335
00:12:49,840 --> 00:12:52,440
of the markings the cat had had around its eyes.

336
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:54,200
She, too, was wearing a cloak,

337
00:12:54,200 --> 00:12:55,360
an emerald one.

338
00:12:55,360 --> 00:12:57,680
Her black hair was drawn into a tight bun.

339
00:12:57,680 --> 00:12:59,440
She looked distinctly ruffled.

340
00:12:59,440 --> 00:13:01,600
"How did you know it was me?" she asked.

341
00:13:01,600 --> 00:13:05,000
"My dear Professor, I 've never 
seen a cat sit so stiffly."

342
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,760
"You'd be stiff if you'd been 
sitting on a brick wall all day,"

343
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:10,360
said Professor McGonagall. "All day?

344
00:13:10,360 --> 00:13:12,000
When you could have been celebrating?

345
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,280
I must have passed a dozen feasts 
and parties on my way here."

346
00:13:15,280 --> 00:13:17,560
Professor McGonagall sniffed angrily.

347
00:13:17,560 --> 00:13:19,960
"Oh yes, everyone's celebrating, all right,"

348
00:13:19,960 --> 00:13:21,400
she said impatiently.

349
00:13:21,400 --> 00:13:23,960
"You'd think they'd be a bit more careful,

350
00:13:23,960 --> 00:13:27,360
but no , even the Muggles have 
noticed something's going on.

351
00:13:27,360 --> 00:13:28,640
It was on their news."

352
00:13:28,640 --> 00:13:32,040
She jerked her head back at the 
Dursleys' dark living-room window.

353
00:13:32,040 --> 00:13:32,920
"I heard it.

354
00:13:32,920 --> 00:13:34,000
Flocks of owls...

355
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:35,280
shooting stars....

356
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:37,520
Well, they're not completely stupid.

357
00:13:37,520 --> 00:13:39,120
They were bound to notice something.

358
00:13:39,120 --> 00:13:40,920
Shooting stars down in Kent ,

359
00:13:40,920 --> 00:13:42,760
I'll bet that was Dedalus Diggle.

360
00:13:42,760 --> 00:13:44,400
He never had much sense."

361
00:13:44,400 --> 00:13:45,520
"You can't blame them,"

362
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:47,120
said Dumbledore gently.

363
00:13:47,120 --> 00:13:50,240
"We've had precious little to 
celebrate for eleven years."

364
00:13:50,240 --> 00:13:51,080
"I know that,"

365
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:53,360
said Professor McGonagall irritably.

366
00:13:53,360 --> 00:13:55,520
"But that's no reason to lose our heads.

367
00:13:55,520 --> 00:13:57,440
People are being downright careless,

368
00:13:57,440 --> 00:13:59,040
out on the streets in broad daylight,

369
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:01,520
not even dressed in Muggle clothes,

370
00:14:01,520 --> 00:14:02,920
swapping rumors."

371
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:04,160
She threw a sharp,

372
00:14:04,160 --> 00:14:06,240
sideways glance at Dumbledore here,

373
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:08,400
as though hoping he was 
going to tell her something,

374
00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:09,320
but he didn't,

375
00:14:09,320 --> 00:14:10,640
so she went on.

376
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,040
"A fine thing it would be if,

377
00:14:12,040 --> 00:14:15,160
on the very day YouKnow-Who seems 
to have disappeared at last,

378
00:14:15,160 --> 00:14:17,200
the Muggles found out about us all.

379
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:18,800
I suppose he really has gone,

380
00:14:18,800 --> 00:14:19,960
Dumbledore?"

381
00:14:19,960 --> 00:14:21,240
"It certainly seems so,"

382
00:14:21,240 --> 00:14:22,520
said Dumbledore.

383
00:14:22,520 --> 00:14:26,200
"We have much to be thankful for. 
Would you care for a lemon drop?"

384
00:14:26,200 --> 00:14:27,040
"A what?"

385
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:30,920
"A lemon drop. They're a kind of 
Muggle sweet I'm rather fond of"

386
00:14:30,920 --> 00:14:32,200
"No, thank you,"

387
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:34,280
said Professor McGonagall coldly,

388
00:14:34,280 --> 00:14:37,240
as though she didn't think this 
was the moment for lemon drops.

389
00:14:37,240 --> 00:14:40,360
"As I say, even if You-Know-Who has gone -"

390
00:14:40,360 --> 00:14:41,480
"My dear Professor,

391
00:14:41,480 --> 00:14:45,160
surely a sensible person like 
yourself can call him by his name?

392
00:14:45,160 --> 00:14:47,360
All this 'You- Know-Who' nonsense ,

393
00:14:47,360 --> 00:14:50,400
for eleven years I have been trying 
to persuade people to call him

394
00:14:50,400 --> 00:14:52,680
by his proper name: Voldemort."

395
00:14:52,680 --> 00:14:54,480
Professor McGonagall flinched,

396
00:14:54,480 --> 00:14:55,520
but Dumbledore,

397
00:14:55,520 --> 00:14:57,520
who was unsticking two lemon drops,

398
00:14:57,520 --> 00:14:59,080
seemed not to notice.

399
00:14:59,080 --> 00:15:00,240
"It all gets so confusing

400
00:15:00,240 --> 00:15:02,480
if we keep saying 'You-Know-Who.'

401
00:15:02,480 --> 00:15:06,280
I have never seen any reason to be 
frightened of saying Voldemort's name.

402
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:07,400
"I know you haven 't,

403
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:08,920
said Professor McGonagall,

404
00:15:08,920 --> 00:15:10,600
sounding half exasperated,

405
00:15:10,600 --> 00:15:11,240
half admiring.

406
00:15:11,240 --> 00:15:11,680
"

407
00:15:11,680 --> 00:15:12,800
But you're different.

408
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:15,440
Everyone knows you're the only one You-Know- oh,

409
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:16,960
all right, Voldemort,

410
00:15:16,960 --> 00:15:18,160
was frightened of."

411
00:15:18,160 --> 00:15:19,080
"You flatter me,"

412
00:15:19,080 --> 00:15:20,640
said Dumbledore calmly.

413
00:15:20,640 --> 00:15:23,160
"Voldemort had powers I will never have."

414
00:15:23,160 --> 00:15:26,000
"Only because you're too , 
well , noble to use them."

415
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:27,440
"It's lucky it's dark.

416
00:15:27,440 --> 00:15:32,200
I haven't blushed so much since Madam 
Pomfrey told me she liked my new earmuffs."

417
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:35,400
Professor McGonagall shot a sharp 
look at Dumbledore and said,

418
00:15:35,400 --> 00:15:38,920
"The owls are nothing next to the 
rumors that are flying around.

419
00:15:38,920 --> 00:15:40,360
You know what everyone's saying?

420
00:15:40,360 --> 00:15:41,960
About why he's disappeared?

421
00:15:41,960 --> 00:15:43,640
About what finally stopped him?"

422
00:15:43,640 --> 00:15:48,440
It seemed that Professor McGonagall had reached 
the point she was most anxious to discuss,

423
00:15:48,440 --> 00:15:50,760
the real reason she had been waiting on a cold,

424
00:15:50,760 --> 00:15:51,920
hard wall all day,

425
00:15:51,920 --> 00:15:54,960
for neither as a cat nor as a 
woman had she fixed Dumbledore

426
00:15:54,960 --> 00:15:57,360
with such a piercing stare as she did now.

427
00:15:57,360 --> 00:15:58,520
It was plain that whatever

428
00:15:58,520 --> 00:15:59,200
"everyone"

429
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:00,040
was saying,

430
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:03,680
she was not going to believe it until 
Dumbledore told her it was true.

431
00:16:03,680 --> 00:16:04,600
Dumbledore,

432
00:16:04,600 --> 00:16:08,120
however, was choosing another 
lemon drop and did not answer.

433
00:16:08,120 --> 00:16:08,920
"What they're saying,"

434
00:16:08,920 --> 00:16:09,920
she pressed on,

435
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:13,160
"is that last night Voldemort 
turned up in Godric's Hollow.

436
00:16:13,160 --> 00:16:14,880
He went to find the Potters.

437
00:16:14,880 --> 00:16:17,560
The rumor is that Lily and James Potter are ,

438
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,080
are , that they're , dead.

439
00:16:19,080 --> 00:16:19,360
"

440
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:22,560
Dumbledore bowed his head. 
Professor McGonagall gasped.

441
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:24,000
"Lily and James...

442
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:25,240
I can't believe it...

443
00:16:25,240 --> 00:16:26,800
I didn't want to believe it...

444
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,000
Oh, Albus..."

445
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:32,040
Dumbledore reached out and 
patted her on the shoulder.

446
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:34,160
"I know... I know..."

447
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:35,400
he said heavily.

448
00:16:35,400 --> 00:16:38,480
Professor McGonagall's voice 
trembled as she went on.

449
00:16:38,480 --> 00:16:39,520
"That's not all.

450
00:16:39,520 --> 00:16:42,560
They're saying he tried to 
kill the Potter's son, Harry.

451
00:16:42,560 --> 00:16:43,600
But , he couldn't.

452
00:16:43,600 --> 00:16:45,400
He couldn't kill that little boy.

453
00:16:45,400 --> 00:16:46,440
No one knows why,

454
00:16:46,440 --> 00:16:49,680
or how, but they're saying that 
when he couldn't kill Harry Potter,

455
00:16:49,680 --> 00:16:51,760
Voldemort's power somehow broke ,

456
00:16:51,760 --> 00:16:53,160
and that's why he's gone.

457
00:16:53,160 --> 00:16:55,080
Dumbledore nodded glumly.

458
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:56,320
"It's , it's true?"

459
00:16:56,320 --> 00:16:58,320
faltered Professor McGonagall.

460
00:16:58,320 --> 00:17:00,120
"After all he's done...

461
00:17:00,120 --> 00:17:01,520
all the people he's killed...

462
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:03,200
he couldn't kill a little boy?

463
00:17:03,200 --> 00:17:04,480
It's just astounding...

464
00:17:04,480 --> 00:17:06,000
of all the things to stop him...

465
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,600
but how in the name of heaven did Harry survive?"

466
00:17:08,600 --> 00:17:09,960
"We can only guess,"

467
00:17:09,960 --> 00:17:11,280
said Dumbledore.

468
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:12,560
"We may never know."

469
00:17:12,560 --> 00:17:15,240
Professor McGonagall pulled 
out a lace handkerchief

470
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:17,880
and dabbed at her eyes beneath her spectacles.

471
00:17:17,880 --> 00:17:22,560
Dumbledore gave a great sniff as he took a 
golden watch from his pocket and examined it.

472
00:17:22,560 --> 00:17:24,320
It was a very odd watch.

473
00:17:24,320 --> 00:17:26,520
It had twelve hands but no numbers;

474
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:29,640
instead, little planets 
were moving around the edge.

475
00:17:29,640 --> 00:17:31,800
It must have made sense to Dumbledore,

476
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:34,560
though, because he put it 
back in his pocket and said,

477
00:17:34,560 --> 00:17:35,760
"Hagrid's late.

478
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:38,160
I suppose it was he who told you I'd be here,

479
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:39,800
by the way?"

480
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:40,280
"Yes,"

481
00:17:40,280 --> 00:17:42,120
said Professor McGonagall.

482
00:17:42,120 --> 00:17:45,040
"And I don't suppose you're 
going to tell me why you're here,

483
00:17:45,040 --> 00:17:46,320
of all places?"

484
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:48,720
"I've come to bring Harry to his aunt and uncle.

485
00:17:48,720 --> 00:17:51,440
They're the only family he has left now."

486
00:17:51,440 --> 00:17:54,480
"You don't mean , you can't 
mean the people who live here?"

487
00:17:54,480 --> 00:17:56,520
cried Professor McGonagall,

488
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:59,280
jumping to her feet and pointing at number four.

489
00:17:59,280 --> 00:18:01,120
"Dumbledore , you can't.

490
00:18:01,120 --> 00:18:02,640
I've been watching them all day.

491
00:18:02,640 --> 00:18:05,200
You couldn't find two people who are less like us.

492
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:06,520
And they've got this son ,

493
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:09,120
I saw him kicking his mother 
all the way up the street,

494
00:18:09,120 --> 00:18:10,720
screaming for sweets.

495
00:18:10,720 --> 00:18:12,680
Harry Potter come and live here!"

496
00:18:12,680 --> 00:18:14,160
"It's the best place for him,"

497
00:18:14,160 --> 00:18:15,840
said Dumbledore firmly.

498
00:18:15,840 --> 00:18:19,880
"His aunt and uncle will be able to 
explain everything to him when he's older.

499
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:21,240
I've written them a letter."

500
00:18:21,240 --> 00:18:21,960
"A letter?"

501
00:18:21,960 --> 00:18:26,040
repeated Professor McGonagall faintly, 
sitting back down on the wall.

502
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:27,560
"Really, Dumbledore,

503
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:29,880
you think you can explain all this in a letter?

504
00:18:29,880 --> 00:18:31,840
These people will never understand him!

505
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:32,800
He'll be famous ,

506
00:18:32,800 --> 00:18:37,840
a legend , I wouldn't be surprised if today 
was known as Harry Potter day in the future ,

507
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:39,760
there will be books written about Harry ,

508
00:18:39,760 --> 00:18:42,240
every child in our world will know his name!"

509
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:43,160
"Exactly,"

510
00:18:43,160 --> 00:18:44,280
said Dumbledore,

511
00:18:44,280 --> 00:18:47,920
looking very seriously over the 
top of his half-moon glasses.

512
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:50,200
"It would be enough to turn any boy's head.

513
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:52,400
Famous before he can walk and talk!

514
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:54,720
Famous for something he won't even remember!

515
00:18:54,720 --> 00:18:57,240
CarA you see how much better off he'll be,

516
00:18:57,240 --> 00:19:00,160
growing up away from all that 
until he's ready to take it?"

517
00:19:00,160 --> 00:19:02,320
Professor McGonagall opened her mouth,

518
00:19:02,320 --> 00:19:03,560
changed her mind,

519
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:05,560
swallowed, and then said,

520
00:19:05,560 --> 00:19:06,640
"Yes , yes,

521
00:19:06,640 --> 00:19:08,440
you're right, of course.

522
00:19:08,440 --> 00:19:09,920
But how is the boy getting here,

523
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:11,000
Dumbledore?"

524
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:15,320
She eyed his cloak suddenly as though she 
thought he might be hiding Harry underneath it.

525
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:16,680
"Hagrid's bringing him."

526
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:17,600
"You think it ,

527
00:19:17,600 --> 00:19:21,560
wise , to trust Hagrid with 
something as important as this?"

528
00:19:21,560 --> 00:19:24,480
I would trust Hagrid with 
my life," said Dumbledore.

529
00:19:24,480 --> 00:19:26,960
"I'm not saying his heart 
isn't in the right place,"

530
00:19:26,960 --> 00:19:29,160
said Professor McGonagall grudgingly,

531
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:31,480
"but you can't pretend he's not careless.

532
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:32,240
He does tend to ,

533
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:33,120
what was that?"

534
00:19:33,120 --> 00:19:36,200
A low rumbling sound had 
broken the silence around them.

535
00:19:36,200 --> 00:19:38,080
It grew steadily louder as they looked up

536
00:19:38,080 --> 00:19:40,440
and down the street for some sign of a headlight;

537
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:43,120
it swelled to a roar as they 
both looked up at the sky ,

538
00:19:43,120 --> 00:19:47,680
and a huge motorcycle fell out of the air 
and landed on the road in front of them.

539
00:19:47,680 --> 00:19:49,280
If the motorcycle was huge,

540
00:19:49,280 --> 00:19:51,640
it was nothing to the man sitting astride it.

541
00:19:51,640 --> 00:19:56,320
He was almost twice as tall as a normal 
man and at least five times as wide.

542
00:19:56,320 --> 00:19:58,400
He looked simply too big to be allowed,

543
00:19:58,400 --> 00:20:03,120
and so wild - long tangles of bushy black 
hair and beard hid most of his face,

544
00:20:03,120 --> 00:20:05,400
he had hands the size of trash can lids,

545
00:20:05,400 --> 00:20:08,320
and his feet in their leather 
boots were like baby dolphins.

546
00:20:08,320 --> 00:20:09,240
In his vast,

547
00:20:09,240 --> 00:20:12,240
muscular arms he was holding a bundle of blankets.

548
00:20:12,240 --> 00:20:12,880
"Hagrid,"

549
00:20:12,880 --> 00:20:15,440
said Dumbledore, sounding relieved.

550
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:18,400
"At last. And where did you get that motorcycle?"

551
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:21,160
"Borrowed it, Professor Dumbledore, sit,"

552
00:20:21,160 --> 00:20:25,200
said the giant, climbing carefully 
off the motorcycle as he spoke.

553
00:20:25,200 --> 00:20:28,680
"Young Sirius Black lent it 
to me. I've got him, sir."

554
00:20:28,680 --> 00:20:30,440
"No problems, were there?"

555
00:20:30,440 --> 00:20:33,400
"No, sir , house was almost destroyed,

556
00:20:33,400 --> 00:20:37,360
but I got him out all right before 
the Muggles started swarmin' around.

557
00:20:37,360 --> 00:20:40,040
He fell asleep as we was flyin' over Bristol."

558
00:20:40,040 --> 00:20:44,840
Dumbledore and Professor McGonagall bent 
forward over the bundle of blankets.

559
00:20:44,840 --> 00:20:46,440
Inside, just visible,

560
00:20:46,440 --> 00:20:47,760
was a baby boy,

561
00:20:47,760 --> 00:20:48,920
fast asleep.

562
00:20:48,920 --> 00:20:53,800
Under a tuft of jet-black hair over his 
forehead they could see a curiously shaped cut,

563
00:20:53,800 --> 00:20:55,280
like a bolt of lightning.

564
00:20:55,280 --> 00:20:56,160
"Is that where -?"

565
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:58,240
whispered Professor McGonagall.

566
00:20:58,240 --> 00:20:58,760
"Yes,"

567
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:00,040
said Dumbledore.

568
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:01,760
"He'll have that scar forever."

569
00:21:01,760 --> 00:21:04,320
"Couldn't you do something about it, Dumbledore?"

570
00:21:04,320 --> 00:21:05,440
"Even if I could,

571
00:21:05,440 --> 00:21:06,280
I wouldn't.

572
00:21:06,280 --> 00:21:08,000
Scars can come in handy.

573
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:12,680
I have one myself above my left knee that 
is a perfect map of the London Underground.

574
00:21:12,680 --> 00:21:14,040
Well , give him here,

575
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:16,480
Hagrid , we'd better get this over with."

576
00:21:16,480 --> 00:21:20,320
Dumbledore took Harry in his arms and 
turned toward the Dursleys' house.

577
00:21:20,320 --> 00:21:22,560
"Could I , could I say good-bye to him, sir?"

578
00:21:22,560 --> 00:21:23,560
asked Hagrid.

579
00:21:23,560 --> 00:21:24,760
He bent his great,

580
00:21:24,760 --> 00:21:28,600
shaggy head over Harry and gave him 
what must have been a very scratchy,

581
00:21:28,600 --> 00:21:29,880
whiskery kiss.

582
00:21:29,880 --> 00:21:30,800
Then, suddenly,

583
00:21:30,800 --> 00:21:33,240
Hagrid let out a howl like a wounded dog.

584
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:34,000
"Shhh!"

585
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:35,520
hissed Professor McGonagall,

586
00:21:35,520 --> 00:21:36,960
"you'll wake the Muggles!"

587
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:37,760
"S-s-sorry,"

588
00:21:37,760 --> 00:21:38,800
sobbed Hagrid,

589
00:21:38,800 --> 00:21:40,080
taking out a large,

590
00:21:40,080 --> 00:21:42,880
spotted handkerchief and burying his face in it.

591
00:21:42,880 --> 00:21:44,560
"But I c-c-can't stand it ,

592
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:45,840
Lily an' James dead ,

593
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:49,600
an' poor little Harry off ter live with Muggles -"

594
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:52,200
"Yes, yes, it's all very sad,

595
00:21:52,200 --> 00:21:53,840
but get a grip on yourself,

596
00:21:53,840 --> 00:21:56,120
Hagrid, or we'll be found,"

597
00:21:56,120 --> 00:21:57,840
Professor McGonagall whispered,

598
00:21:57,840 --> 00:22:02,080
patting Hagrid gingerly on the arm as 
Dumbledore stepped over the low garden wall

599
00:22:02,080 --> 00:22:03,680
and walked to the front door.

600
00:22:03,680 --> 00:22:05,720
He laid Harry gently on the doorstep,

601
00:22:05,720 --> 00:22:07,240
took a letter out of his cloak,

602
00:22:07,240 --> 00:22:09,320
tucked it inside Harry's blankets,

603
00:22:09,320 --> 00:22:11,200
and then came back to the other two.

604
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:14,600
For a full minute the three of them 
stood and looked at the little bundle;

605
00:22:14,600 --> 00:22:16,120
Hagrid's shoulders shook,

606
00:22:16,120 --> 00:22:18,440
Professor McGonagall blinked furiously,

607
00:22:18,440 --> 00:22:23,000
and the twinkling light that usually shone 
from Dumbledore's eyes seemed to have gone out.

608
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:23,400
"Well,"

609
00:22:23,400 --> 00:22:24,960
said Dumbledore finally,

610
00:22:24,960 --> 00:22:25,800
"that's that.

611
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:27,560
We've no business staying here.

612
00:22:27,560 --> 00:22:30,680
We may as well go and join the celebrations."

613
00:22:30,680 --> 00:22:31,000
"Yeah,"

614
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:33,000
said Hagrid in a very muffled voice,

615
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,440
"I'll be takin' Sirius his bike back.

616
00:22:35,440 --> 00:22:37,240
G'night, Professor McGonagall ,

617
00:22:37,240 --> 00:22:38,240
Professor Dumbledore,

618
00:22:38,240 --> 00:22:39,080
sir."

619
00:22:39,080 --> 00:22:41,440
Wiping his streaming eyes on his jacket sleeve,

620
00:22:41,440 --> 00:22:45,360
Hagrid swung himself onto the motorcycle 
and kicked the engine into life;

621
00:22:45,360 --> 00:22:48,400
with a roar it rose into the 
air and off into the night.

622
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:51,920
"I shall see you soon, I 
expect, Professor McGonagall,"

623
00:22:51,920 --> 00:22:53,000
said Dumbledore,

624
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:54,240
nodding to her.

625
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:56,880
Professor McGonagall blew her nose in reply.

626
00:22:56,880 --> 00:22:59,720
Dumbledore turned and walked back down the street.

627
00:22:59,720 --> 00:23:02,840
On the corner he stopped and 
took out the silver Put-Outer.

628
00:23:02,840 --> 00:23:03,920
He clicked it once,

629
00:23:03,920 --> 00:23:06,840
and twelve balls of light sped 
back to their street lamps so

630
00:23:06,840 --> 00:23:09,200
that Privet Drive glowed suddenly orange

631
00:23:09,200 --> 00:23:11,920
and he could make out a tabby 
cat slinking around the corner

632
00:23:11,920 --> 00:23:13,600
at the other end of the street.

633
00:23:13,600 --> 00:23:16,960
He could just see the bundle of 
blankets on the step of number four.

634
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:18,200
"Good luck, Harry,"

635
00:23:18,200 --> 00:23:19,120
he murmured.

636
00:23:19,120 --> 00:23:21,640
He turned on his heel and 
with a swish of his cloak,

637
00:23:21,640 --> 00:23:22,760
he was gone.

638
00:23:22,760 --> 00:23:25,360
A breeze ruffled the neat hedges of Privet Drive,

639
00:23:25,360 --> 00:23:28,120
which lay silent and tidy under the inky sky,

640
00:23:28,120 --> 00:23:32,320
the very last place you would 
expect astonishing things to happen.

641
00:23:32,320 --> 00:23:35,920
Harry Potter rolled over inside 
his blankets without waking up.

642
00:23:35,920 --> 00:23:39,520
One small hand closed on the 
letter beside him and he slept on,

643
00:23:39,520 --> 00:23:41,000
not knowing he was special,

644
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:42,600
not knowing he was famous,

645
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:43,760
not knowing he would be woken

646
00:23:43,760 --> 00:23:47,480
in a few hours' time by Mrs. Dursley's 
scream as she opened the front door

647
00:23:47,480 --> 00:23:49,240
to put out the milk bottles,

648
00:23:49,240 --> 00:23:51,520
nor that he would spend the 
next few weeks being prodded

649
00:23:51,520 --> 00:23:53,400
and pinched by his cousin Dudley...

650
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:55,480
He couldn't know that at this very moment,

651
00:23:55,480 --> 00:23:59,080
people meeting in secret all over the 
country were holding up their glasses

652
00:23:59,080 --> 00:24:00,880
and saying in hushed voices:

653
00:24:00,880 --> 00:24:03,960
"To Harry Potter , the boy who lived!"

654
00:24:03,960 --> 00:24:05,000
CHAPTER TWO

655
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:06,560
THE VANISHING GLASS

656
00:24:06,560 --> 00:24:10,600
Nearly ten years had passed since the 
Dursleys had woken up to find their nephew

657
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:11,760
on the front step,

658
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:14,520
but Privet Drive had hardly changed at all.

659
00:24:14,520 --> 00:24:16,760
The sun rose on the same tidy front gardens

660
00:24:16,760 --> 00:24:19,800
and lit up the brass number four 
on the Dursleys' front door;

661
00:24:19,800 --> 00:24:21,680
it crept into their living room,

662
00:24:21,680 --> 00:24:24,360
which was almost exactly the 
same as it had been on the night

663
00:24:24,360 --> 00:24:28,080
when Mr. Dursley had seen that 
fateful news report about the owls.

664
00:24:28,080 --> 00:24:32,240
Only the photographs on the mantelpiece 
really showed how much time had passed.

665
00:24:32,240 --> 00:24:33,280
Ten years ago,

666
00:24:33,280 --> 00:24:34,720
there had been lots of pictures of

667
00:24:34,720 --> 00:24:38,200
what looked like a large pink beach 
ball wearing different-colored bonnets ,

668
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:40,920
but Dudley Dursley was no longer a baby,

669
00:24:40,920 --> 00:24:45,000
and now the photographs showed a large 
blond boy riding his first bicycle,

670
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:46,880
on a carousel at the fair,

671
00:24:46,880 --> 00:24:49,000
playing a computer game with his father,

672
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:51,320
being hugged and kissed by his mother.

673
00:24:51,320 --> 00:24:55,080
The room held no sign at all that 
another boy lived in the house, too.

674
00:24:55,080 --> 00:24:57,120
Yet Harry Potter was still there,

675
00:24:57,120 --> 00:24:58,480
asleep at the moment,

676
00:24:58,480 --> 00:24:59,680
but not for long.

677
00:24:59,680 --> 00:25:01,120
His Aunt Petunia was awake

678
00:25:01,120 --> 00:25:04,600
and it was her shrill voice that 
made the first noise of the day.

679
00:25:04,600 --> 00:25:06,680
"Up! Get up! Now!"

680
00:25:06,680 --> 00:25:10,120
Harry woke with a start. His 
aunt rapped on the door again.

681
00:25:10,120 --> 00:25:10,560
"Up!"

682
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:11,640
she screeched.

683
00:25:11,640 --> 00:25:13,640
Harry heard her walking toward the kitchen

684
00:25:13,640 --> 00:25:16,560
and then the sound of the frying 
pan being put on the stove.

685
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:20,520
He rolled onto his back and tried to 
remember the dream he had been having.

686
00:25:20,520 --> 00:25:21,840
It had been a good one.

687
00:25:21,840 --> 00:25:24,080
There had been a flying motorcycle in it.

688
00:25:24,080 --> 00:25:27,120
He had a funny feeling he'd 
had the same dream before.

689
00:25:27,120 --> 00:25:29,120
His aunt was back outside the door.

690
00:25:29,120 --> 00:25:30,160
"Are you up yet?"

691
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:31,320
she demanded.

692
00:25:31,320 --> 00:25:31,880
"Nearly,"

693
00:25:31,880 --> 00:25:33,000
said Harry.

694
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:34,640
"Well, get a move on,

695
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:36,480
I want you to look after the bacon.

696
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:38,000
And don't you dare let it burn,

697
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,600
I want everything perfect on Duddy's birthday."

698
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:41,640
Harry groaned.

699
00:25:41,640 --> 00:25:42,680
"What did you say?"

700
00:25:42,680 --> 00:25:44,520
his aunt snapped through the door.

701
00:25:44,520 --> 00:25:46,360
"Nothing, nothing..."

702
00:25:46,360 --> 00:25:47,440
Dudley's birthday ,

703
00:25:47,440 --> 00:25:48,880
how could he have forgotten?

704
00:25:48,880 --> 00:25:52,160
Harry got slowly out of bed 
and started looking for socks.

705
00:25:52,160 --> 00:25:53,960
He found a pair under his bed and,

706
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:56,440
after pulling a spider off one of them,

707
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:57,440
put them on.

708
00:25:57,440 --> 00:25:59,120
Harry was used to spiders,

709
00:25:59,120 --> 00:26:01,560
because the cupboard under 
the stairs was full of them,

710
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,080
and that was where he slept.

711
00:26:03,080 --> 00:26:05,840
When he was dressed he went 
down the hall into the kitchen.

712
00:26:05,840 --> 00:26:09,720
The table was almost hidden beneath 
all Dudley's birthday presents.

713
00:26:09,720 --> 00:26:12,720
It looked as though Dudley had 
gotten the new computer he wanted,

714
00:26:12,720 --> 00:26:16,040
not to mention the second 
television and the racing bike.

715
00:26:16,040 --> 00:26:19,560
Exactly why Dudley wanted a racing 
bike was a mystery to Harry,

716
00:26:19,560 --> 00:26:22,480
as Dudley was very fat and hated exercise ,

717
00:26:22,480 --> 00:26:24,960
unless of course it involved punching somebody.

718
00:26:24,960 --> 00:26:27,160
Dudley's favorite punching bag was Harry,

719
00:26:27,160 --> 00:26:28,920
but he couldn't often catch him.

720
00:26:28,920 --> 00:26:30,080
Harry didn't look it,

721
00:26:30,080 --> 00:26:31,800
but he was very fast.

722
00:26:31,800 --> 00:26:34,640
Perhaps it had something to do 
with living in a dark cupboard,

723
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:37,920
but Harry had always been 
small and skinny for his age.

724
00:26:37,920 --> 00:26:40,600
He looked even smaller and 
skinnier than he really was

725
00:26:40,600 --> 00:26:43,480
because all he had to wear 
were old clothes of Dudley's,

726
00:26:43,480 --> 00:26:46,480
and Dudley was about four 
times bigger than he was.

727
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:47,960
Harry had a thin face,

728
00:26:47,960 --> 00:26:49,080
knobbly knees,

729
00:26:49,080 --> 00:26:49,920
black hair,

730
00:26:49,920 --> 00:26:51,400
and bright green eyes.

731
00:26:51,400 --> 00:26:54,600
He wore round glasses held 
together with a lot of Scotch tape

732
00:26:54,600 --> 00:26:57,600
because of all the times Dudley 
had punched him on the nose.

733
00:26:57,600 --> 00:27:01,040
The only thing Harry liked about his 
own appearance was a very thin scar

734
00:27:01,040 --> 00:27:02,400
on his forehead that was shaped

735
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:03,800
like a bolt of lightning.

736
00:27:03,800 --> 00:27:05,880
He had had it as long as he could remember,

737
00:27:05,880 --> 00:27:09,360
and the first question he could ever 
remember asking his Aunt Petunia was

738
00:27:09,360 --> 00:27:10,560
how he had gotten it.

739
00:27:10,560 --> 00:27:12,640
"In the car crash when your parents died,"

740
00:27:12,640 --> 00:27:13,720
she had said.

741
00:27:13,720 --> 00:27:15,360
"And don't ask questions."

742
00:27:15,360 --> 00:27:16,640
Don't ask questions ,

743
00:27:16,640 --> 00:27:19,960
that was the first rule for a 
quiet life with the Dursleys.

744
00:27:19,960 --> 00:27:23,600
Uncle Vernon entered the kitchen as 
Harry was turning over the bacon.

745
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:24,640
"Comb your hair!"

746
00:27:24,640 --> 00:27:27,360
he barked, by way of a morning greeting.

747
00:27:27,360 --> 00:27:28,440
About once a week,

748
00:27:28,440 --> 00:27:33,200
Uncle Vernon looked over the top of his newspaper 
and shouted that Harry needed a haircut.

749
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:36,800
Harry must have had more haircuts than 
the rest of the boys in his class put

750
00:27:36,800 --> 00:27:38,680
together, but it made no difference,

751
00:27:38,680 --> 00:27:40,240
his hair simply grew that way ,

752
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:41,640
all over the place.

753
00:27:41,640 --> 00:27:45,680
Harry was frying eggs by the time Dudley 
arrived in the kitchen with his mother.

754
00:27:45,680 --> 00:27:47,880
Dudley looked a lot like Uncle Vernon.

755
00:27:47,880 --> 00:27:49,400
He had a large pink face,

756
00:27:49,400 --> 00:27:50,480
not much neck,

757
00:27:50,480 --> 00:27:52,440
small, watery blue eyes,

758
00:27:52,440 --> 00:27:56,120
and thick blond hair that lay 
smoothly on his thick, fat head.

759
00:27:56,120 --> 00:27:59,400
Aunt Petunia often said that 
Dudley looked like a baby angel ,

760
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:02,520
Harry often said that Dudley 
looked like a pig in a wig.

761
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:05,200
Harry put the plates of 
egg and bacon on the table,

762
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:07,320
which was difficult as there wasn't much room.

763
00:28:07,320 --> 00:28:08,680
Dudley, meanwhile,

764
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:10,400
was counting his presents.

765
00:28:10,400 --> 00:28:11,480
His face fell.

766
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:12,280
"Thirty-six,"

767
00:28:12,280 --> 00:28:15,240
he said, looking up at his mother and father.

768
00:28:15,240 --> 00:28:16,960
"That's two less than last year."

769
00:28:16,960 --> 00:28:19,840
"Darling, you haven't counted 
Auntie Marge's present,

770
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:23,040
see, it's here under this big 
one from Mommy and Daddy."

771
00:28:23,040 --> 00:28:24,880
"All right, thirty-seven then,"

772
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:25,760
said Dudley,

773
00:28:25,760 --> 00:28:27,440
going red in the face.

774
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:30,720
Harry, who could see a huge 
Dudley tantrum coming on,

775
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:35,800
began wolfing down his bacon as fast as 
possible in case Dudley turned the table over.

776
00:28:35,800 --> 00:28:38,040
Aunt Petunia obviously scented danger,

777
00:28:38,040 --> 00:28:39,920
too, because she said quickly,

778
00:28:39,920 --> 00:28:42,880
"And we'll buy you another two 
presents while we're out today.

779
00:28:42,880 --> 00:28:44,480
How's that, popkin?

780
00:28:44,480 --> 00:28:45,880
Two more presents.

781
00:28:45,880 --> 00:28:47,440
Is that all right''

782
00:28:47,440 --> 00:28:49,040
Dudley thought for a moment.

783
00:28:49,040 --> 00:28:50,600
It looked like hard work.

784
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:52,080
Finally he said slowly,

785
00:28:52,080 --> 00:28:54,400
"So I'll have thirty ... thirty..."

786
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:56,120
"Thirty-nine, sweetums,"

787
00:28:56,120 --> 00:28:57,520
said Aunt Petunia.

788
00:28:57,520 --> 00:28:58,160
"Oh."

789
00:28:58,160 --> 00:29:01,320
Dudley sat down heavily and 
grabbed the nearest parcel.

790
00:29:01,320 --> 00:29:02,280
"All right then."

791
00:29:02,280 --> 00:29:03,760
Uncle Vernon chuckled.

792
00:29:03,760 --> 00:29:05,520
"Little tyke wants his money's worth,

793
00:29:05,520 --> 00:29:06,800
just like his father.

794
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:08,800
'Atta boy, Dudley!"

795
00:29:08,800 --> 00:29:10,520
He ruffled Dudley's hair.

796
00:29:10,520 --> 00:29:12,040
At that moment the telephone rang

797
00:29:12,040 --> 00:29:14,520
and Aunt Petunia went to answer it while Harry

798
00:29:14,520 --> 00:29:17,520
and Uncle Vernon watched 
Dudley unwrap the racing bike,

799
00:29:17,520 --> 00:29:18,680
a video camera,

800
00:29:18,680 --> 00:29:20,440
a remote control airplane,

801
00:29:20,440 --> 00:29:23,520
sixteen new computer games, and a VCR.

802
00:29:23,520 --> 00:29:25,600
He was ripping the paper off a gold wristwatch

803
00:29:25,600 --> 00:29:30,000
when Aunt Petunia came back from the 
telephone looking both angry and worried.

804
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:31,960
"Bad news, Vernon," she said.

805
00:29:31,960 --> 00:29:35,040
"Mrs. Figg's broken her leg. She can't take him."

806
00:29:35,040 --> 00:29:37,280
She jerked her head in Harry's direction.

807
00:29:37,280 --> 00:29:39,440
Dudley's mouth fell open in horror,

808
00:29:39,440 --> 00:29:41,280
but Harry's heart gave a leap.

809
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:42,960
Every year on Dudley's birthday,

810
00:29:42,960 --> 00:29:45,480
his parents took him and a friend out for the day,

811
00:29:45,480 --> 00:29:46,880
to adventure parks,

812
00:29:46,880 --> 00:29:48,160
hamburger restaurants,

813
00:29:48,160 --> 00:29:49,440
or the movies.

814
00:29:49,440 --> 00:29:50,280
Every year,

815
00:29:50,280 --> 00:29:52,560
Harry was left behind with Mrs. Figg,

816
00:29:52,560 --> 00:29:55,200
a mad old lady who lived two streets away.

817
00:29:55,200 --> 00:29:56,640
Harry hated it there.

818
00:29:56,640 --> 00:29:58,200
The whole house smelled of cabbage

819
00:29:58,200 --> 00:30:02,440
and Mrs. Figg made him look at photographs 
of all the cats she'd ever owned.

820
00:30:02,440 --> 00:30:03,120
"Now what?"

821
00:30:03,120 --> 00:30:04,320
said Aunt Petunia,

822
00:30:04,320 --> 00:30:07,200
looking furiously at Harry 
as though he'd planned this.

823
00:30:07,200 --> 00:30:10,760
Harry knew he ought to feel sorry 
that Mrs. Figg had broken her leg,

824
00:30:10,760 --> 00:30:13,680
but it wasn't easy when he reminded 
himself it would be a whole year

825
00:30:13,680 --> 00:30:15,520
before he had to look at Tibbles,

826
00:30:15,520 --> 00:30:17,240
Snowy, Mr. Paws,

827
00:30:17,240 --> 00:30:18,560
and Tufty again.

828
00:30:18,560 --> 00:30:19,600
"We could phone Marge,"

829
00:30:19,600 --> 00:30:21,280
Uncle Vernon suggested.

830
00:30:21,280 --> 00:30:24,400
"Don't be silly, Vernon, she hates the boy."

831
00:30:24,400 --> 00:30:27,000
The Dursleys often spoke about Harry like this,

832
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:28,360
as though he wasn't there ,

833
00:30:28,360 --> 00:30:32,320
or rather, as though he was something 
very nasty that couldn't understand them,

834
00:30:32,320 --> 00:30:33,440
like a slug.

835
00:30:33,440 --> 00:30:36,320
"What about what's-her-name, 
your friend , Yvonne?"

836
00:30:36,320 --> 00:30:37,880
"On vacation in Majorca,"

837
00:30:37,880 --> 00:30:39,440
snapped Aunt Petunia.

838
00:30:39,440 --> 00:30:40,880
"You could just leave me here,"

839
00:30:40,880 --> 00:30:43,600
Harry put in hopefully (he'd be able to watch

840
00:30:43,600 --> 00:30:48,320
what he wanted on television for a change and 
maybe even have a go on Dudley's computer).

841
00:30:48,320 --> 00:30:51,120
Aunt Petunia looked as though 
she'd just swallowed a lemon.

842
00:30:51,120 --> 00:30:53,320
"And come back and find the house in ruins?"

843
00:30:53,320 --> 00:30:54,400
she snarled.

844
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:55,640
"I won't blow up the house,"

845
00:30:55,640 --> 00:30:58,000
said Harry, but they weren't listening.

846
00:30:58,000 --> 00:30:59,800
"I suppose we could take him to the zoo,"

847
00:30:59,800 --> 00:31:01,120
said Aunt Petunia slowly,

848
00:31:01,120 --> 00:31:03,400
"... and leave him in the car...."

849
00:31:03,400 --> 00:31:06,360
"That car's new, he's not sitting in it alone...."

850
00:31:06,360 --> 00:31:08,280
Dudley began to cry loudly.

851
00:31:08,280 --> 00:31:10,000
In fact, he wasn't really crying ,

852
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:12,920
it had been years since he'd really cried ,

853
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:15,640
but he knew that if he screwed 
up his face and wailed,

854
00:31:15,640 --> 00:31:17,960
his mother would give him anything he wanted.

855
00:31:17,960 --> 00:31:18,520
"Dinky Duddydums,

856
00:31:19,160 --> 00:31:22,400
don't cry, Mummy won't let 
him spoil your special day!"

857
00:31:22,400 --> 00:31:25,280
she cried, flinging her arms around him.

858
00:31:25,280 --> 00:31:28,440
"I... don't... want... him... t-t-to come!"

859
00:31:28,440 --> 00:31:31,400
Dudley yelled between huge, pretend sobs.

860
00:31:31,400 --> 00:31:33,600
"He always sp- spoils everything!"

861
00:31:33,600 --> 00:31:37,200
He shot Harry a nasty grin through 
the gap in his mother's arms.

862
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:39,120
Just then, the doorbell rang ,

863
00:31:39,120 --> 00:31:41,000
"Oh, good Lord, they're here!"

864
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:42,720
said Aunt Petunia frantically ,

865
00:31:42,720 --> 00:31:43,960
and a moment later,

866
00:31:43,960 --> 00:31:45,280
Dudley's best friend,

867
00:31:45,280 --> 00:31:46,480
Piers Polkiss,

868
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:47,920
walked in with his mother.

869
00:31:47,920 --> 00:31:50,720
Piers was a scrawny boy with a face like a rat.

870
00:31:50,720 --> 00:31:55,080
He was usually the one who held people's arms 
behind their backs while Dudley hit them.

871
00:31:55,080 --> 00:31:57,360
Dudley stopped pretending to cry at once.

872
00:31:57,360 --> 00:31:58,600
Half an hour later,

873
00:31:58,600 --> 00:32:00,560
Harry, who couldn't believe his luck,

874
00:32:00,560 --> 00:32:03,920
was sitting in the back of the 
Dursleys' car with Piers and Dudley,

875
00:32:03,920 --> 00:32:06,640
on the way to the zoo for 
the first time in his life.

876
00:32:06,640 --> 00:32:10,560
His aunt and uncle hadn't been able to 
think of anything else to do with him,

877
00:32:10,560 --> 00:32:11,960
but before they'd left,

878
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:14,360
Uncle Vernon had taken Harry aside.

879
00:32:14,360 --> 00:32:15,120
"I'm warning you,"

880
00:32:15,120 --> 00:32:19,040
he had said, putting his large purple 
face right up close to Harry's,

881
00:32:19,040 --> 00:32:20,200
"I'm warning you now,

882
00:32:20,200 --> 00:32:22,040
boy , any funny business,

883
00:32:22,040 --> 00:32:23,000
anything at all ,

884
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:25,680
and you'll be in that cupboard 
from now until Christmas."

885
00:32:25,680 --> 00:32:27,120
"I'm not going to do anything,"

886
00:32:27,120 --> 00:32:29,000
said Harry, "honestly..

887
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:32,440
But Uncle Vernon didn't 
believe him. No one ever did.

888
00:32:32,440 --> 00:32:33,480
The problem was,

889
00:32:33,480 --> 00:32:35,880
strange things often happened around Harry

890
00:32:35,880 --> 00:32:39,960
and it was just no good telling the 
Dursleys he didn't make them happen.

891
00:32:39,960 --> 00:32:41,360
Once, Aunt Petunia,

892
00:32:41,360 --> 00:32:45,600
tired of Harry coming back from the barbers 
looking as though he hadn't been at all,

893
00:32:45,600 --> 00:32:47,360
had taken a pair of kitchen scissors

894
00:32:47,360 --> 00:32:50,960
and cut his hair so short he was 
almost bald except for his bangs,

895
00:32:50,960 --> 00:32:51,560
which she left

896
00:32:51,560 --> 00:32:53,520
"to hide that horrible scar."

897
00:32:53,520 --> 00:32:55,840
Dudley had laughed himself silly at Harry,

898
00:32:55,840 --> 00:32:59,120
who spent a sleepless night 
imagining school the next day,

899
00:32:59,120 --> 00:33:03,600
where he was already laughed at for 
his baggy clothes and taped glasses.

900
00:33:03,600 --> 00:33:04,440
Next morning,

901
00:33:04,440 --> 00:33:07,480
however, he had gotten up to find 
his hair exactly as it had been

902
00:33:07,480 --> 00:33:11,960
before Aunt Petunia had sheared it off He had 
been given a week in his cupboard for this,

903
00:33:11,960 --> 00:33:14,400
even though he had tried to 
explain that he couldn't explain

904
00:33:14,400 --> 00:33:16,520
how it had grown back so quickly.

905
00:33:16,520 --> 00:33:17,480
Another time,

906
00:33:17,480 --> 00:33:22,000
Aunt Petunia had been trying to force him into 
a revolting old sweater of Dudley's (brown

907
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:23,680
with orange puff balls) ,

908
00:33:23,680 --> 00:33:26,120
The harder she tried to pull it over his head,

909
00:33:26,120 --> 00:33:27,880
the smaller it seemed to become,

910
00:33:27,880 --> 00:33:30,520
until finally it might have fitted a hand puppet,

911
00:33:30,520 --> 00:33:32,440
but certainly wouldn't fit Harry.

912
00:33:32,440 --> 00:33:35,880
Aunt Petunia had decided it must 
have shrunk in the wash and,

913
00:33:35,880 --> 00:33:37,240
to his great relief,

914
00:33:37,240 --> 00:33:38,800
Harry wasn't punished.

915
00:33:38,800 --> 00:33:39,720
On the other hand,

916
00:33:39,720 --> 00:33:43,840
he'd gotten into terrible trouble for being 
found on the roof of the school kitchens.

917
00:33:43,840 --> 00:33:46,640
Dudley's gang had been chasing him as usual when,

918
00:33:46,640 --> 00:33:49,200
as much to Harry's surprise as anyone else's,

919
00:33:49,200 --> 00:33:50,920
there he was sitting on the chimney.

920
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:53,280
The Dursleys had received a very angry letter

921
00:33:53,280 --> 00:33:57,200
from Harry's headmistress telling them 
Harry had been climbing school buildings.

922
00:33:57,200 --> 00:33:59,240
But all he'd tried to do (as he shouted

923
00:33:59,240 --> 00:34:00,840
at Uncle Vernon through the locked door

924
00:34:00,840 --> 00:34:05,440
of his cupboard) was jump behind the big 
trash cans outside the kitchen doors.

925
00:34:05,440 --> 00:34:08,440
Harry supposed that the wind must 
have caught him in mid- jump.

926
00:34:08,440 --> 00:34:10,920
But today, nothing was going to go wrong.

927
00:34:10,920 --> 00:34:12,480
It was even worth being with Dudley

928
00:34:12,480 --> 00:34:15,360
and Piers to be spending the day 
somewhere that wasn't school,

929
00:34:15,360 --> 00:34:16,120
his cupboard,

930
00:34:16,120 --> 00:34:18,760
or Mrs. Figg's cabbage-smelling living room.

931
00:34:18,760 --> 00:34:19,760
While he drove,

932
00:34:19,760 --> 00:34:22,160
Uncle Vernon complained to Aunt Petunia.

933
00:34:22,160 --> 00:34:25,240
He liked to complain about things: people at work,

934
00:34:25,240 --> 00:34:26,920
Harry, the council,

935
00:34:26,920 --> 00:34:28,360
Harry, the bank,

936
00:34:28,360 --> 00:34:31,480
and Harry were just a few 
of his favorite subjects.

937
00:34:31,480 --> 00:34:32,000
This morning,

938
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:32,880
it was motorcycles.

939
00:34:32,880 --> 00:34:36,360
"... roaring along like 
maniacs, the young hoodlums,"

940
00:34:36,360 --> 00:34:38,960
he said, as a motorcycle overtook them.

941
00:34:38,960 --> 00:34:40,420
I had a dream about a motorcycle,

942
00:34:40,420 --> 00:34:43,120
" said Harry, remembering suddenly. "

943
00:34:43,120 --> 00:34:44,200
It was flying."

944
00:34:44,200 --> 00:34:47,120
Uncle Vernon nearly crashed into the car in front.

945
00:34:47,120 --> 00:34:49,840
He turned right around in 
his seat and yelled at Harry,

946
00:34:49,840 --> 00:34:52,560
his face like a gigantic beet with a mustache:

947
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:54,360
"MOTORCYCLES DON'T FLY!"

948
00:34:54,360 --> 00:34:56,120
Dudley and Piers sniggered.

949
00:34:56,120 --> 00:34:56,760
I know they don't,

950
00:34:56,760 --> 00:34:58,000
" said Harry. "

951
00:34:58,000 --> 00:34:59,400
It was only a dream."

952
00:34:59,400 --> 00:35:01,440
But he wished he hadn't said anything.

953
00:35:01,440 --> 00:35:05,160
If there was one thing the Dursleys hated 
even more than his asking questions,

954
00:35:05,160 --> 00:35:08,360
it was his talking about anything 
acting in a way it shouldn't,

955
00:35:08,360 --> 00:35:11,240
no matter if it was in a dream or even a cartoon ,

956
00:35:11,240 --> 00:35:14,040
they seemed to think he might get dangerous ideas.

957
00:35:14,040 --> 00:35:17,960
It was a very sunny Saturday and 
the zoo was crowded with families.

958
00:35:17,960 --> 00:35:22,640
The Dursleys bought Dudley and Piers large 
chocolate ice creams at the entrance and then,

959
00:35:22,640 --> 00:35:25,200
because the smiling lady 
in the van had asked Harry

960
00:35:25,200 --> 00:35:28,080
what he wanted before they could hurry him away,

961
00:35:28,080 --> 00:35:30,160
they bought him a cheap lemon ice pop.

962
00:35:30,160 --> 00:35:31,320
It wasn't bad,

963
00:35:31,320 --> 00:35:32,800
either, Harry thought,

964
00:35:32,800 --> 00:35:35,160
licking it as they watched a 
gorilla scratching its head

965
00:35:35,160 --> 00:35:37,200
who looked remarkably like Dudley,

966
00:35:37,200 --> 00:35:38,920
except that it wasn't blond.

967
00:35:38,920 --> 00:35:41,600
Harry had the best morning 
he'd had in a long time.

968
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:45,960
He was careful to walk a little way apart 
from the Dursleys so that Dudley and Piers,

969
00:35:45,960 --> 00:35:48,960
who were starting to get bored 
with the animals by lunchtime,

970
00:35:48,960 --> 00:35:51,880
wouldn't fall back on their 
favorite hobby of hitting him.

971
00:35:51,880 --> 00:35:53,440
They ate in the zoo restaurant,

972
00:35:53,440 --> 00:35:54,840
and when Dudley had a tantrum

973
00:35:54,840 --> 00:35:58,440
because his knickerbocker glory 
didn't have enough ice cream on top,

974
00:35:58,440 --> 00:36:02,640
Uncle Vernon bought him another one and 
Harry was allowed to finish the first.

975
00:36:02,640 --> 00:36:03,560
Harry felt,

976
00:36:03,560 --> 00:36:06,960
afterward, that he should have 
known it was all too good to last.

977
00:36:06,960 --> 00:36:09,200
After lunch they went to the reptile house.

978
00:36:09,200 --> 00:36:10,840
It was cool and dark in there,

979
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:13,040
with lit windows all along the walls.

980
00:36:13,040 --> 00:36:14,120
Behind the glass,

981
00:36:14,120 --> 00:36:18,480
all sorts of lizards and snakes were crawling 
and slithering over bits of wood and stone.

982
00:36:18,480 --> 00:36:20,560
Dudley and Piers wanted to see huge,

983
00:36:20,560 --> 00:36:22,360
poisonous cobras and thick,

984
00:36:22,360 --> 00:36:24,160
man-crushing pythons.

985
00:36:24,160 --> 00:36:27,120
Dudley quickly found the 
largest snake in the place.

986
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:30,280
It could have wrapped its body 
twice around Uncle Vernon's car

987
00:36:30,280 --> 00:36:32,400
and crushed it into a trash can ,

988
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:34,600
but at the moment it didn't look in the mood.

989
00:36:34,600 --> 00:36:36,640
In fact, it was fast asleep.

990
00:36:36,640 --> 00:36:39,160
Dudley stood with his nose 
pressed against the glass,

991
00:36:39,160 --> 00:36:41,480
staring at the glistening brown coils.

992
00:36:41,480 --> 00:36:42,320
"Make it move,"

993
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:43,840
he whined at his father.

994
00:36:43,840 --> 00:36:45,760
Uncle Vernon tapped on the glass,

995
00:36:45,760 --> 00:36:47,320
but the snake didn't budge.

996
00:36:47,320 --> 00:36:48,280
"Do it again,"

997
00:36:48,280 --> 00:36:49,360
Dudley ordered.

998
00:36:49,360 --> 00:36:52,360
Uncle Vernon rapped the glass 
smartly with his knuckles,

999
00:36:52,360 --> 00:36:54,320
but the snake just snoozed on.

1000
00:36:54,320 --> 00:36:55,280
"This is boring,"

1001
00:36:55,280 --> 00:36:57,640
Dudley moaned. He shuffled away.

1002
00:36:57,640 --> 00:37:01,160
Harry moved in front of the tank 
and looked intently at the snake.

1003
00:37:01,160 --> 00:37:04,600
He wouldn't have been surprised 
if it had died of boredom itself ,

1004
00:37:04,600 --> 00:37:07,240
no company except stupid 
people drumming their fingers

1005
00:37:07,240 --> 00:37:10,080
on the glass trying to disturb it all day long.

1006
00:37:10,080 --> 00:37:12,600
It was worse than having a cupboard as a bedroom,

1007
00:37:12,600 --> 00:37:16,520
where the only visitor was Aunt Petunia 
hammering on the door to wake you up;

1008
00:37:16,520 --> 00:37:19,120
at least he got to visit the rest of the house.

1009
00:37:19,120 --> 00:37:21,840
The snake suddenly opened its beady eyes.

1010
00:37:21,840 --> 00:37:23,320
Slowly, very slowly,

1011
00:37:23,320 --> 00:37:27,560
it raised its head until its eyes were 
on a level with Harry's. It winked.

1012
00:37:27,560 --> 00:37:28,600
Harry stared.

1013
00:37:28,600 --> 00:37:32,200
Then he looked quickly around 
to see if anyone was watching.

1014
00:37:32,200 --> 00:37:33,160
They weren't.

1015
00:37:33,160 --> 00:37:35,760
He looked back at the snake and winked, too.

1016
00:37:35,760 --> 00:37:38,760
The snake jerked its head 
toward Uncle Vernon and Dudley,

1017
00:37:38,760 --> 00:37:41,320
then raised its eyes to the ceiling.

1018
00:37:41,320 --> 00:37:44,160
It gave Harry a look that said quite plainly:

1019
00:37:44,160 --> 00:37:45,680
"I get that all the time.

1020
00:37:45,680 --> 00:37:46,240
"I know,"

1021
00:37:46,240 --> 00:37:47,880
Harry murmured through the glass,

1022
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:50,400
though he wasn't sure the snake could hear him.

1023
00:37:50,400 --> 00:37:52,040
"It must be really annoying."

1024
00:37:52,040 --> 00:37:53,840
The snake nodded vigorously.

1025
00:37:53,840 --> 00:37:55,800
"Where do you come from, anyway?"

1026
00:37:55,800 --> 00:37:56,920
Harry asked.

1027
00:37:56,920 --> 00:38:00,320
The snake jabbed its tail at a 
little sign next to the glass.

1028
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:02,160
Harry peered at it.

1029
00:38:02,160 --> 00:38:04,160
Boa Constrictor, Brazil.

1030
00:38:04,160 --> 00:38:05,280
"Was it nice there?"

1031
00:38:05,280 --> 00:38:07,960
The boa constrictor jabbed 
its tail at the sign again

1032
00:38:07,960 --> 00:38:11,840
and Harry read on: This 
specimen was bred in the zoo.

1033
00:38:11,840 --> 00:38:15,000
"Oh, I see , so you've never been to Brazil?"

1034
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:16,480
As the snake shook its head,

1035
00:38:16,480 --> 00:38:20,520
a deafening shout behind Harry 
made both of them jump. "DUDLEY!

1036
00:38:20,520 --> 00:38:22,120
MR. DURSLEY!

1037
00:38:22,120 --> 00:38:23,600
COME AND LOOK AT THIS SNAKE!

1038
00:38:23,600 --> 00:38:25,240
YOU WON'T BELIEVE WHAT IT'S DOING!"

1039
00:38:25,240 --> 00:38:27,440
Dudley came waddling toward 
them as fast as he could.

1040
00:38:28,080 --> 00:38:29,320
"Out of the way, you,"

1041
00:38:29,320 --> 00:38:31,800
he said, punching Harry in the ribs.

1042
00:38:31,800 --> 00:38:32,960
Caught by surprise,

1043
00:38:32,960 --> 00:38:35,320
Harry fell hard on the concrete floor.

1044
00:38:35,320 --> 00:38:38,760
What came next happened so fast 
no one saw how it happened ,

1045
00:38:38,760 --> 00:38:39,640
one second,

1046
00:38:39,640 --> 00:38:43,080
Piers and Dudley were leaning 
right up close to the glass,

1047
00:38:43,080 --> 00:38:45,760
the next, they had leapt 
back with howls of horror.

1048
00:38:45,760 --> 00:38:47,320
Harry sat up and gasped;

1049
00:38:47,320 --> 00:38:50,560
the glass front of the boa 
constrictor's tank had vanished.

1050
00:38:50,560 --> 00:38:53,120
The great snake was uncoiling itself rapidly,

1051
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:54,960
slithering out onto the floor.

1052
00:38:54,960 --> 00:38:59,640
People throughout the reptile house 
screamed and started running for the exits.

1053
00:38:59,640 --> 00:39:01,800
As the snake slid swiftly past him,

1054
00:39:01,800 --> 00:39:03,280
Harry could have sworn a low,

1055
00:39:03,280 --> 00:39:04,960
hissing voice said,

1056
00:39:04,960 --> 00:39:08,720
"Brazil, here I come.... Thanksss, amigo."

1057
00:39:08,720 --> 00:39:11,200
The keeper of the reptile house was in shock.

1058
00:39:11,200 --> 00:39:12,120
"But the glass,"

1059
00:39:12,120 --> 00:39:13,080
he kept saying,

1060
00:39:13,080 --> 00:39:14,480
"where did the glass go?"

1061
00:39:14,480 --> 00:39:17,880
The zoo director himself made 
Aunt Petunia a cup of strong,

1062
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:21,400
sweet tea while he apologized over and over again.

1063
00:39:21,400 --> 00:39:23,520
Piers and Dudley could only gibber.

1064
00:39:23,520 --> 00:39:25,040
As far as Harry had seen,

1065
00:39:25,040 --> 00:39:29,280
the snake hadn't done anything except snap 
playfully at their heels as it passed,

1066
00:39:29,280 --> 00:39:32,320
but by the time they were all 
back in Uncle Vernon's car,

1067
00:39:32,320 --> 00:39:35,600
Dudley was telling them how it 
had nearly bitten off his leg,

1068
00:39:35,600 --> 00:39:38,560
while Piers was swearing it had 
tried to squeeze him to death.

1069
00:39:38,560 --> 00:39:39,480
But worst of all,

1070
00:39:39,480 --> 00:39:40,720
for Harry at least,

1071
00:39:40,720 --> 00:39:42,880
was Piers calming down enough to say,

1072
00:39:42,880 --> 00:39:45,840
"Harry was talking to it, weren't you, Harry?"

1073
00:39:45,840 --> 00:39:50,680
Uncle Vernon waited until Piers was safely 
out of the house before starting on Harry.

1074
00:39:50,680 --> 00:39:53,160
He was so angry he could hardly speak.

1075
00:39:53,160 --> 00:39:54,400
He managed to say,

1076
00:39:54,400 --> 00:39:56,880
"Go , cupboard , stay , no meals,"

1077
00:39:56,880 --> 00:39:58,960
before he collapsed into a chair,

1078
00:39:58,960 --> 00:40:02,800
and Aunt Petunia had to run 
and get him a large brandy.

1079
00:40:02,800 --> 00:40:05,000
Harry lay in his dark cupboard much later,

1080
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:06,640
wishing he had a watch.

1081
00:40:06,640 --> 00:40:10,920
He didn't know what time it was and he 
couldn't be sure the Dursleys were asleep yet.

1082
00:40:10,920 --> 00:40:11,880
Until they were,

1083
00:40:11,880 --> 00:40:14,640
he couldn't risk sneaking to 
the kitchen for some food.

1084
00:40:14,640 --> 00:40:17,040
He'd lived with the Dursleys almost ten years,

1085
00:40:17,040 --> 00:40:18,440
ten miserable years,

1086
00:40:18,440 --> 00:40:20,040
as long as he could remember,

1087
00:40:20,040 --> 00:40:24,040
ever since he'd been a baby and his 
parents had died in that car crash.

1088
00:40:24,040 --> 00:40:27,640
He couldn't remember being in the 
car when his parents had died.

1089
00:40:27,640 --> 00:40:31,160
Sometimes, when he strained his memory 
during long hours in his cupboard,

1090
00:40:31,160 --> 00:40:34,560
he came up with a strange vision: 
a blinding flash of green light

1091
00:40:34,560 --> 00:40:36,800
and a burn- ing pain on his forehead.

1092
00:40:36,800 --> 00:40:37,880
This, he supposed,

1093
00:40:37,880 --> 00:40:38,920
was the crash,

1094
00:40:38,920 --> 00:40:41,960
though he couldn't imagine where 
all the green light came from.

1095
00:40:41,960 --> 00:40:44,160
He couldn't remember his parents at all.

1096
00:40:44,160 --> 00:40:46,240
His aunt and uncle never spoke about them,

1097
00:40:46,240 --> 00:40:48,840
and of course he was forbidden to ask questions.

1098
00:40:48,840 --> 00:40:51,360
There were no photographs of them in the house.

1099
00:40:51,360 --> 00:40:52,600
When he had been younger,

1100
00:40:52,600 --> 00:40:56,680
Harry had dreamed and dreamed of some 
unknown relation coming to take him away,

1101
00:40:56,680 --> 00:40:58,120
but it had never happened;

1102
00:40:58,120 --> 00:41:00,240
the Dursleys were his only family.

1103
00:41:00,240 --> 00:41:05,040
Yet sometimes he thought (or maybe hoped) that 
strangers in the street seemed to know him.

1104
00:41:05,040 --> 00:41:07,480
Very strange strangers they were, too.

1105
00:41:07,480 --> 00:41:11,840
A tiny man in a violet top hat had bowed to 
him once while out shopping with Aunt Petunia

1106
00:41:11,840 --> 00:41:12,880
and Dudley.

1107
00:41:12,880 --> 00:41:15,840
After asking Harry furiously if he knew the man,

1108
00:41:15,840 --> 00:41:19,320
Aunt Petunia had rushed them out of 
the shop without buying anything.

1109
00:41:19,320 --> 00:41:24,560
A wild-looking old woman dressed all in 
green had waved merrily at him once on a bus.

1110
00:41:24,560 --> 00:41:28,400
A bald man in a very long purple 
coat had actually shaken his hand

1111
00:41:28,400 --> 00:41:29,720
in the street the other day

1112
00:41:29,720 --> 00:41:31,720
and then walked away without a word.

1113
00:41:31,720 --> 00:41:34,000
The weirdest thing about 
all these people was the way

1114
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:37,520
they seemed to vanish the second 
Harry tried to get a closer look.

1115
00:41:37,520 --> 00:41:39,640
At school, Harry had no one.

1116
00:41:39,640 --> 00:41:44,120
Everybody knew that Dudley's gang hated that 
odd Harry Potter in his baggy old clothes

1117
00:41:44,120 --> 00:41:45,560
and broken glasses,

1118
00:41:45,560 --> 00:41:48,440
and nobody liked to disagree with Dudley's gang.

1119
00:41:48,440 --> 00:41:49,160
CHAPTER THREE

1120
00:41:49,160 --> 00:41:50,800
THE LETTERS FROM NO ONE

1121
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:55,640
The escape of the Brazilian boa constrictor 
earned Harry his longest-ever punishment.

1122
00:41:55,640 --> 00:41:57,960
By the time he was allowed 
out of his cupboard again,

1123
00:41:57,960 --> 00:42:02,600
the summer holidays had started and Dudley 
had already broken his new video camera,

1124
00:42:02,600 --> 00:42:04,920
crashed his remote control airplane,

1125
00:42:04,920 --> 00:42:07,640
and, first time out on his racing bike,

1126
00:42:07,640 --> 00:42:11,680
knocked down old Mrs. Figg as she 
crossed Privet Drive on her crutches.

1127
00:42:11,680 --> 00:42:13,520
Harry was glad school was over,

1128
00:42:13,520 --> 00:42:15,720
but there was no escaping Dudley's gang,

1129
00:42:15,720 --> 00:42:17,960
who visited the house every single day.

1130
00:42:17,960 --> 00:42:19,320
Piers, Dennis,

1131
00:42:19,320 --> 00:42:22,120
Malcolm, and Gordon were all big and stupid,

1132
00:42:22,120 --> 00:42:25,120
but as Dudley was the biggest 
and stupidest of the lot,

1133
00:42:25,120 --> 00:42:26,320
he was the leader.

1134
00:42:26,320 --> 00:42:31,120
The rest of them were all quite happy to join 
in Dudley's favorite sport: Harry Hunting.

1135
00:42:31,120 --> 00:42:34,680
This was why Harry spent as much 
time as possible out of the house,

1136
00:42:34,680 --> 00:42:37,600
wandering around and thinking 
about the end of the holidays,

1137
00:42:37,600 --> 00:42:39,760
where he could see a tiny ray of hope.

1138
00:42:39,760 --> 00:42:43,200
When September came he would be 
going off to secondary school and,

1139
00:42:43,200 --> 00:42:44,840
for the first time in his life,

1140
00:42:44,840 --> 00:42:46,280
he wouldn't be with Dudley.

1141
00:42:46,280 --> 00:42:50,520
Dudley had been accepted at Uncle 
Vernon's old private school, Smeltings.

1142
00:42:50,520 --> 00:42:52,520
Piers Polkiss was going there too.

1143
00:42:52,520 --> 00:42:54,000
Harry, on the other hand,

1144
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:55,680
was going to Stonewall High,

1145
00:42:55,680 --> 00:42:57,200
the local public school.

1146
00:42:57,200 --> 00:42:59,200
Dudley thought this was very funny.

1147
00:42:59,200 --> 00:43:02,640
"They stuff people's heads down the 
toilet the first day at Stonewall,"

1148
00:43:02,640 --> 00:43:03,840
he told Harry.

1149
00:43:03,840 --> 00:43:05,960
"Want to come upstairs and practice?"

1150
00:43:05,960 --> 00:43:06,960
"No, thanks,"

1151
00:43:06,960 --> 00:43:07,880
said Harry.

1152
00:43:07,880 --> 00:43:11,560
"The poor toilet's never had anything 
as horrible as your head down it ,

1153
00:43:11,560 --> 00:43:12,920
it might be sick."

1154
00:43:12,920 --> 00:43:16,240
Then he ran, before Dudley 
could work out what he'd said.

1155
00:43:16,240 --> 00:43:17,400
One day in July,

1156
00:43:17,400 --> 00:43:20,560
Aunt Petunia took Dudley to London 
to buy his Smeltings uniform,

1157
00:43:20,560 --> 00:43:22,560
leaving Harry at Mrs. Figg's.

1158
00:43:22,560 --> 00:43:24,800
Mrs. Figg wasn 't as bad as usual.

1159
00:43:24,800 --> 00:43:28,280
It turned out she'd broken her 
leg tripping over one of her cats,

1160
00:43:28,280 --> 00:43:31,120
and she didn't seem quite 
as fond of them as before.

1161
00:43:31,120 --> 00:43:32,800
She let Harry watch television

1162
00:43:32,800 --> 00:43:37,240
and gave him a bit of chocolate cake that 
tasted as though she'd had it for several years.

1163
00:43:37,240 --> 00:43:37,960
That evening,

1164
00:43:37,960 --> 00:43:41,840
Dudley paraded around the living room 
for the family in his brand-new uniform.

1165
00:43:41,840 --> 00:43:44,120
Smeltings' boys wore maroon tailcoats,

1166
00:43:44,120 --> 00:43:45,480
orange knickerbockers,

1167
00:43:45,480 --> 00:43:47,800
and flat straw hats called boaters.

1168
00:43:47,800 --> 00:43:49,480
They also carried knobbly sticks,

1169
00:43:49,480 --> 00:43:52,400
used for hitting each other while 
the teachers weren't looking.

1170
00:43:52,400 --> 00:43:55,720
This was supposed to be good 
training for later life.

1171
00:43:55,720 --> 00:43:58,040
As he looked at Dudley in his new knickerbockers,

1172
00:43:58,040 --> 00:44:02,200
Uncle Vernon said gruffly that it 
was the proudest moment of his life.

1173
00:44:02,200 --> 00:44:06,400
Aunt Petunia burst into tears and said she 
couldn't believe it was her Ickle Dudleykins,

1174
00:44:06,400 --> 00:44:08,480
he looked so handsome and grown-up.

1175
00:44:08,480 --> 00:44:10,640
Harry didn't trust himself to speak.

1176
00:44:10,640 --> 00:44:14,480
He thought two of his ribs might already 
have cracked from trying not to laugh.

1177
00:44:14,480 --> 00:44:16,920
There was a horrible smell in 
the kitchen the next morning

1178
00:44:16,920 --> 00:44:18,880
when Harry went in for breakfast.

1179
00:44:18,880 --> 00:44:21,880
It seemed to be coming from a 
large metal tub in the sink.

1180
00:44:21,880 --> 00:44:23,200
He went to have a look.

1181
00:44:23,200 --> 00:44:26,880
The tub was full of what looked like 
dirty rags swimming in gray water.

1182
00:44:26,880 --> 00:44:27,800
"What's this?"

1183
00:44:27,800 --> 00:44:29,280
he asked Aunt Petunia.

1184
00:44:29,280 --> 00:44:32,640
Her lips tightened as they always 
did if he dared to ask a question.

1185
00:44:32,640 --> 00:44:34,800
"Your new school uniform," she said.

1186
00:44:34,800 --> 00:44:36,600
Harry looked in the bowl again.

1187
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:37,000
"Oh,"

1188
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:40,000
he said, "I didn't realize it had to be so wet."

1189
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:41,080
"DotA be stupid,"

1190
00:44:41,080 --> 00:44:42,520
snapped Aunt Petunia.

1191
00:44:42,520 --> 00:44:45,160
"I'm dyeing some of Dudley's 
old things gray for you.

1192
00:44:45,160 --> 00:44:47,840
It'll look just like everyone 
else's when I've finished."

1193
00:44:47,840 --> 00:44:49,680
Harry seriously doubted this,

1194
00:44:49,680 --> 00:44:51,600
but thought it best not to argue.

1195
00:44:51,600 --> 00:44:54,080
He sat down at the table 
and tried not to think about

1196
00:44:54,080 --> 00:44:57,200
how he was going to look on his 
first day at Stonewall High ,

1197
00:44:57,200 --> 00:45:00,720
like he was wearing bits of 
old elephant skin, probably.

1198
00:45:00,720 --> 00:45:02,720
Dudley and Uncle Vernon came in,

1199
00:45:02,720 --> 00:45:06,440
both with wrinkled noses because of 
the smell from Harry's new uniform.

1200
00:45:06,440 --> 00:45:10,880
Uncle Vernon opened his newspaper as usual 
and Dudley banged his Smelting stick,

1201
00:45:10,880 --> 00:45:12,280
which he carried everywhere,

1202
00:45:12,280 --> 00:45:13,320
on the table.

1203
00:45:13,320 --> 00:45:16,960
They heard the click of the mail slot 
and flop of letters on the doormat.

1204
00:45:16,960 --> 00:45:18,400
"Get the mail, Dudley,"

1205
00:45:18,400 --> 00:45:20,800
said Uncle Vernon from behind his paper.

1206
00:45:20,800 --> 00:45:22,000
"Make Harry get it."

1207
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:23,720
"Get the mail, Harry."

1208
00:45:23,720 --> 00:45:24,960
"Make Dudley get it."

1209
00:45:24,960 --> 00:45:27,440
"Poke him with your Smelting stick, Dudley."

1210
00:45:27,440 --> 00:45:30,400
Harry dodged the Smelting 
stick and went to get the mail.

1211
00:45:30,400 --> 00:45:34,640
Three things lay on the doormat: a 
postcard from Uncle Vernon's sister Marge,

1212
00:45:34,640 --> 00:45:36,840
who was vacationing on the Isle of Wight,

1213
00:45:36,840 --> 00:45:38,960
a brown envelope that looked like a bill,

1214
00:45:38,960 --> 00:45:40,600
and , a letter for Harry.

1215
00:45:40,600 --> 00:45:42,480
Harry picked it up and stared at it,

1216
00:45:42,480 --> 00:45:45,320
his heart twanging like a giant elastic band.

1217
00:45:45,320 --> 00:45:46,560
No one, ever,

1218
00:45:46,560 --> 00:45:47,640
in his whole life,

1219
00:45:47,640 --> 00:45:49,600
had written to him. Who would?

1220
00:45:49,600 --> 00:45:50,800
He had no friends,

1221
00:45:50,800 --> 00:45:51,960
no other relatives ,

1222
00:45:51,960 --> 00:45:53,720
he didn't belong to the library,

1223
00:45:53,720 --> 00:45:56,920
so he'd never even got rude 
notes asking for books back.

1224
00:45:57,480 --> 00:45:58,320
Yet here it was,

1225
00:45:58,320 --> 00:46:02,320
a letter, addressed so plainly 
there could be no mistake:

1226
00:46:02,320 --> 00:46:03,920
Mr. H. Potter

1227
00:46:03,920 --> 00:46:05,040
The Cupboard under the Stairs

1228
00:46:05,040 --> 00:46:06,560
4 Privet Drive

1229
00:46:06,560 --> 00:46:07,640
Little Whinging

1230
00:46:07,640 --> 00:46:08,560
Surrey

1231
00:46:08,560 --> 00:46:10,480
The envelope was thick and heavy,

1232
00:46:10,480 --> 00:46:12,040
made of yellowish parchment,

1233
00:46:12,040 --> 00:46:14,600
and the address was written in emerald-green ink.

1234
00:46:14,600 --> 00:46:15,880
There was no stamp.

1235
00:46:15,880 --> 00:46:17,400
Turning the envelope over,

1236
00:46:17,400 --> 00:46:18,600
his hand trembling,

1237
00:46:18,600 --> 00:46:21,760
Harry saw a purple wax seal 
bearing a coat of arms;

1238
00:46:21,760 --> 00:46:23,360
a lion, an eagle,

1239
00:46:23,360 --> 00:46:26,920
a badger, and a snake 
surrounding a large letter H.

1240
00:46:26,920 --> 00:46:28,240
"Hurry up, boy!"

1241
00:46:28,240 --> 00:46:30,320
shouted Uncle Vernon from the kitchen.

1242
00:46:30,320 --> 00:46:32,880
"What are you doing, checking for letter bombs?"

1243
00:46:32,880 --> 00:46:34,600
He chuckled at his own joke.

1244
00:46:34,600 --> 00:46:36,080
Harry went back to the kitchen,

1245
00:46:36,080 --> 00:46:37,720
still staring at his letter.

1246
00:46:37,720 --> 00:46:40,400
He handed Uncle Vernon the bill and the postcard,

1247
00:46:40,400 --> 00:46:43,960
sat down, and slowly began 
to open the yellow envelope.

1248
00:46:43,960 --> 00:46:45,840
Uncle Vernon ripped open the bill,

1249
00:46:45,840 --> 00:46:47,160
snorted in disgust,

1250
00:46:47,160 --> 00:46:48,840
and flipped over the postcard.

1251
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:49,760
"Marge's ill,"

